(41, 11, 20, 40, 13, 6, 6, 'from the roots', 'Connection of Withering and Roots', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of withering due to a lack of roots. Mark describes a fig tree that is ''dried up from the roots,'' while Matthew notes that plants ''had no root'' and withered away. This connection highlights the importance of roots for sustaining life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 20, 41, 11, 14, 14, NULL, 'Fig Tree Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the fate of the fig tree. In Mark 11:14, Jesus declares that no man will eat fruit from it, and in Mark 11:20, the disciples observe the tree dried up, illustrating the fulfillment of that declaration.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 20, 43, 15, 6, 6, NULL, 'Withering and Abiding', 'This connection highlights the theme of withering due to lack of vitality. Both passages emphasize the consequence of being disconnected from a source of life, whether it be the fig tree or the branch.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 20, 23, 40, 24, 24, 'dried up from the roots', 'Fig Tree and Withering', 'This connection highlights the theme of withering and lack of root. Both passages emphasize the idea of something being dried up or withered, suggesting a loss of vitality.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 20, 18, 18, 16, 17, 'dried up from the roots', 'Dried Roots and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of destruction, specifically the drying up of roots as a sign of judgment. In Mark, the fig tree''s roots are dried up, while in Job, the imagery of dried roots signifies the demise of the wicked.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 20, 18, 20, 5, 7, 'dried up from the roots', 'Short-lived Triumph of the Wicked', 'This connection highlights the theme of the transient nature of success and the ultimate downfall of the wicked. In Mark, the fig tree''s drying up symbolizes the end of false appearances, paralleling Job''s assertion that the joy of the hypocrite is fleeting.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 21, 20, 3, 33, 33, 'cursedst is withered away', 'Connection of Cursing and Blessing', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and its consequences. In Mark, the withered fig tree represents the curse, while Proverbs contrasts this with the blessing of the just.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 21, 38, 5, 3, 4, 'cursedst is withered away', 'Curse and Withering Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of curses leading to destruction. In Mark, the withering of the fig tree represents a curse, while in Zechariah, the curse consumes the houses of wrongdoers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 21, 40, 23, 7, 7, NULL, 'Authority and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages. In Mark, the withering of the fig tree signifies the consequences of unfruitfulness, while in Matthew, the emphasis on being called ''Rabbi'' reflects a desire for recognition and authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 21, 40, 25, 41, 41, 'cursedst', 'Cursing and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of cursing and its consequences. In Mark, the fig tree is cursed and withers, while in Matthew, those cursed are sent away into everlasting fire.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 21, 46, 16, 22, 22, NULL, 'Judgment and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. The withering of the fig tree represents a consequence of cursing, while the anathema in 1 Corinthians signifies a severe judgment for those who do not love Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
